Protecting Break Glass Accounts in Entra: Adapting to MFA Enforcement
As Microsoft strengthens security across its platforms, Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) is becoming mandatory for more administrative portals. This development underscores the need to revisit and enhance the security of break glass accounts. Relying solely on a username and password, even if complex, is no longer a viable approach.

This shift aligns with Microsoft’s Secure Future Initiative, a response to the growing sophistication of cyber threats. Launched after a critical U.S. Cyber Safety Review Board (CSRB) report on a significant cyber incident, the initiative focuses on addressing vulnerabilities, enhancing authentication, and reducing reliance on outdated models like passwords. For detailed insights, see Microsoft’s official report.

Current and Upcoming MFA Enforcement on Admin Portals
MFA is already enforced on several admin portals, and more are being added. Importantly, this enforcement applies to break glass accounts, even if they are excluded from Conditional Access policies.

Key MFA Enforcements
Azure Portal: MFA is mandatory for all privileged roles.
Azure DevOps: MFA enforcement is implemented for portal access.
Microsoft 365 Admin Center: Starting February 3, 2025, MFA will be rolled out gradually, with notifications sent 30 days prior to enforcement for specific tenants. Refer to the official announcement.
