Enhancing Protection with Authentication Method Policies
Authentication method policies offer greater control over allowed methods, ensuring compliance with security best practices.

Policy Example
In a secure environment:

Enabled: Passkeys, Microsoft Authenticator, Email OTP.
Disabled: SMS, Hardware OATH tokens, Third-party OATH tokens, Voice calls, Certificate-based authentication.
Exclusions: Break glass accounts and legacy service accounts are excluded from certain policies, while restricted by Conditional Access policies.
Temporary Access Pass (TAP) can be used during account setup, with strict time limits and group membership for TAP-enabled users.

Creating and Securing a Break Glass Account with a FIDO2 Key
Here’s how to set up a secure break glass account:

1. Account Creation
Generate an account in Azure AD with a strong, temporary password.
Assign privileged roles and exclude the account from all Conditional Access policies.
2. Register a FIDO2 Security Key
Access Security Info: Sign in and navigate to My Profile > Security Info.
Add Method: Choose "Security key" and follow the prompts to register.
Test Access: Verify the account can access necessary portals with the FIDO2 key.
